ce:section.ce:para:
A classic method of nitroblue tetrazolium (NBT) chromogenic was used. The superoxide anion (O2




                           −
                        ) is produced by the xanthine and xanthine oxidase reaction system, and the nitroblue tetrazolium is reduced to blue formazan, which has strong absorption at 560 nm. SOD can scavenge superoxide anions, thereby inhibiting the development of hyperthyroidism. The darker the blue of the reaction solution is, the lower the activity of the superoxide dismutase is and vice versa. Accordingly, the level of superoxide dismutase activity can be calculated by colorimetric analysis. First, cells were harvested and washed 1∼2 times with PBS or saline precooled in 4 °C or an ice bath. The pellet was homogenized with precooled PBS at 4 °C or in an ice bath (various common electric homogenizers could be used). The homogenate was then centrifuged at 4 °C, and the supernatant was sampled for test. An appropriate amount of NBT/enzyme working solution was placed in a volume of 160 μL per reaction. By uniformly mixing 158 μL of SOD detection buffer, 1 μL of NBT and 1 μL of enzyme solution, 160 μL of NBT/enzyme working solution was configured. The prepared NBT/enzyme working solution was kept at 4 °C or in an ice bath. The third step of the experiment was to prepare a reaction start working fluid. The fluid was composed of 39 μL of SOD detection buffer and 1 μL of reaction start solution. Finally, the aforementioned solution was mixed in a 96-well plate, and the absorbance of the sample was detected at 560 nm by a microplate reader. This protocol was repeated 4 times for each sample. The sample without treatment by CQDs or other drugs served as the control group, the inhibition rate of which was considered as 0. The detection of SOD activities of NIH 3T3 cells and red blood cells followed the same procedure.
